  <li id="comment-18943" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://www.vintageholiday.typepad.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">amy</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2009/12/for-ever-and-ever/#comment-18943"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2010-01-06T04:18:42-05:00">Wednesday, January 6, 2010 at 4:18 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>caramel corn is part of my childhood&#8230;.<br />On a snowy Midwestern day when I was about five years old, my mother and I were running errands and I was getting increasingly cranky.. she said that if I was patient, a treat would come my way. I stopped squirming. She steered the car into the parking lot of a local sweet shop,  and said ‚ÄúStay here‚Äù and bought a bag of fresh hot caramel corn.  I sat in the back seat salivating.  I was eager to dive in, but she said, &#8220;Not yet!&#8221; instructing me to close the wax paper bag tightly so the heat wouldn‚Äôt escape. </p>
<p>When we arrived home a few minutes later, I ran into the house. ‚ÄúWait!‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúThere‚Äôs only one rule. You can‚Äôt use your hands to eat it.‚Äù We carefully peeled back the steaming bag and there on the kitchen table, with our heads down, like two pigs at a trough, we snarfed the warm delicious treat.  We giggled and smacked our lips, laughing at each other while kernels stuck to our cheeks and noses. It was pure sugary magic.</p>
<p>Enjoy!</p>
<p>Amy</p>
    </div>

